    </header>
    <h3>Fight Club Monkey – The First Person Shooters</h3>

    <p>Under the guise of
      <em>Fight Cub Monkey</em>, the clan has played a number of different FPS games over the years, including:</p>
    <ul class="default">
      <li>Urban Terror</li>
      <li>Medal of Honor: Allied Assault</li>
      <li>Soldier of Fortune</li>
      <li>Battlefield 1942</li>
      <li>Unreal Tournament 2003/4</li>
      <li>Team Fortress 2</li>
      <li>Battlefield Bad Company 2</li>
    </ul>
    <h3><em>Fellowship of the Monkey</em> – Neocron</h3>

    <p>Our Neocron (NC) guild was called <em>Fellowship of the Monkey</em> (FotM) and belonged to the
      <em>Fallen Angels</em> faction, primarily based within
      <em>Tech Haven</em>. We remained fairly small, generally only inviting our friends into the guild. Eventually,
      once the game became boring (it was plagued with bugs and problems) most of the members quit the game, and
      everyone that was left was absorbed into
      <em>The Shattered Star Confederation</em> (SSC).</p>

    <h3><em>The Army of the 12 Monkeys</em> – Dark Age of Camelot</h3>

    <p>Our Dark Age of Camelot (DAoC) guild was called <em>The Army of the 12 Monkeys</em> (A12M), and was based within
      the realm of Midgard. Although our main base of operations was within <em>FortAtla</em> (and the nearby island
      nicked named <em>MonkeyIsland</em>), we would explore the entire realm on our travels.. even enter other realms to
      do battle, and protect our own realm from invasion.</p>

    <p>A12M was much larger than FotM, with us inviting both friends, and people we met within the game, to join the
      guild. It was also far more organised than FotM, and we often planned player events, and ensured that we always
      supported our crafters with money and items. We eventually stopped playing the game due to other commitments, so
      invited our members to join one of the guilds within the alliance we started. We’re still good friends with a lot
      of the people we met via DAoC.</p>

    <h3><em>The League of Extraordinary Monkeys</em> – World of WarCraft</h3>

    <p>Several long-term members of FcM were participants in the World of Warcraft (WoW) beta, and when the game went
      live in 2005 they quickly established a new guild on the Arathor server. Named
      <em>The League of Extraordinary Monkeys</em>, the guild sought to follow the ideals we’d worked so hard on in
      DAoC.</p>

    <p>With no official social hang-out for the Arathor server on the official forums, The League took matters into
      their own hands. Daniel registered an Arathor domain name and cultivated a forum which became so popular
      among the server populace that it’s hosting had to be upgraded several times.</p>

    <p>The guild remained active as far as The Burning Crusade expansion, before other commitments and newer games
      resulted in our dispersal. Those of us who remember, have extremely fond memories of our time in WoW, but
      generally agree that it’s time has passed.</p>

    <h3><em>Fullmetal Monkey</em> – Diablo III</h3>

    <p>Diablo III (D3) was the latest point and click RPG from Blizzard. D3 supports up to 4 players in a cooperative
      environment as they battle through a world populated by zombies, monsters and demons, with the sole aim of
      defeating Diablo himself (in addition to collecting some ‘phat loot’).</p>

    <p>Although D3 doesn’t support an in-game guild system, we wanted to stick with our tradition of giving our RPG
      games a new name, so decided upon <strong>Fullmetal Monkey</strong> (<em><strong>FM</strong>)</em>, inspired by
      the manga and anime <em>Fullmetal Alchemist</em>.</p>
  </div>
